  "prompt": "Why does water spread grease and oil fires?",
  "response": "Water spreads grease and oil fires due to differences in density and the nature of oil and grease. When water is poured onto a grease or oil fire, the water sinks underneath the oil because water is denser. As the water heats up and turns into steam, it expands rapidly and can cause the oil to splatter, spreading the oil and potentially the fire. Additionally, since oil and water do not mix, the water fails to cool the fuel effectively, further exacerbating the fire.\n\nIt's crucial to use proper fire suppression methods for grease and oil fires, such as covering the pan with a lid to cut off the oxygen supply, using a fire extinguisher rated for oil fires (Class B or K), or applying baking soda or salt to smother the flames. Never use water, as it can make the situation more dangerous.",
